-- 
India Equity: Airlines, State Refiners, Sugar Companies, Coal

-- B y   A m e y a   K a r v e
-- 
2011-06-24T11:46:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-24/india-equity-movers-aviation-sugar-companies-coal-india-max.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  India  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and prices are as of the 3:30 p.m. close in Mumbai.  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or Sensex, rose
513.19, or 2.9 percent, to 18,240.68, the steepest gain since
March 1. The BSE 200 Index added 2.7 percent to 2,249.48.  Airline Stocks: Jet Airways (India) Ltd. (JETIN IN), the
nation’s largest carrier, surged 14 percent to 469.15 rupees,
the biggest gain since March 2010, following a tumble in crude
prices.  Kingfisher Airlines Ltd. (KAIR)  , the second-biggest
jumped 8.5 percent to 38.9 rupees, and  SpiceJet Ltd. (SJET)  ,
the nation’s only listed low-cost carrier, soared by its daily
20 percent limit to 32.6 rupees, the steepest advance since July
2008.  State Refiners: Indian Oil Corp. (IOCL IN), the biggest,
rose 2.5 percent to 336.9 rupees as the government may raise
fuel prices when a group of ministers meets today, an oil
ministry official said. Bharat Petroleum Corp. (BPCL IN), the
second-biggest, climbed 2.8 percent to 634.7 rupees and
Hindustan Petroleum Corp. (HPCL IN) jumped 6.1 percent to 392.6
rupees. All three had the highest closing price in more than a
month.  Sugar Companies:  Bajaj Hindusthan Ltd. (BJH)  , the
country’s biggest sugar producer, rose 2.8 percent to 65.3
rupees, the steepest advance since May 27 after the government
allowed additional exports. Mills and traders have been
permitted to ship 500,000 metric tons, Rural Development
Minister Vilasrao Deshmukh said yesterday after markets closed.  Balrampur Chini Mills Ltd. (BRCM)  , the second-biggest
producer, climbed 3.4 percent to 59.65 rupees and  Shree Renuka
Sugars Ltd. (SHRS)  , the biggest refiner, gained 4.2 percent
to 60.45 rupees.  Coal India Ltd. (COAL)  , the world’s biggest producer,
added 3.7 percent to 390 rupees, the steepest rise in more than
six weeks. The company has sought the government’s approval to
buy stakes in “unlisted units of overseas-listed companies,”
Chairman N.C. Jha said in  New Delhi  yesterday after the markets
closed.  Jaiprakash Power Ventures Ltd. (JPVL)   increased 2.4
percent to 44.65 rupees after the power generator was rated
“underperform” in new coverage at First Global Securities Ltd.  LIC Housing Finance Ltd. (LICHF)   increased 2.6 percent
to 227.6 rupees, the biggest gain since May 30. The home-loan
arm of India’s largest insurer was rated new “underperform” at
Macquarie Research by equity analyst Mudit Painuly.  Max India Ltd. (MAX)   gained 1.2 percent to 178.6 rupees,
the highest closing price in more than a week. Five million
shares, or 2.2 percent of the hospital chain operator’s equity,
changed hands on the National Stock Exchange in a single trade
at an average price of 180 rupees, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. Buyers and sellers weren’t immediately known.  Ranbaxy Laboratories Ltd. (RBXY)   jumped 4.6 percent to
535.35 rupees, the steepest advance since May 30. The U.S.  Food
and Drug Administration  has started inspecting a new
manufacturing facility of India’s biggest drugmaker at Mohali in
Punjab, the Economic Times reported, citing two unidentified
persons. If the inspection is successful, it could pave the way
for Ranbaxy to start supplying drugs to the U.S. market almost
three years after they were halted from its two main plants, the
report said.  To contact the reporters on this story:
